If an Abipon die from being pierced with many wounds, or from hav- ing his bones broken, or his strength exhausted by extreme old age, his countrymenall deny that wounds or weakness occasioned his death, and anxiously try to discover by which of the jugglers, and for what reason he was killed. Because they have remeinbered some of their nation to have lived for a hundred years, they imagine that they would never die, were it not for the jugglers and the Spaniards. What ri- diculous ideas do not the Americans entertain respecting the eclipse of the sun and moon! During the time it lasts, the Abipones fill the air with horrid lamentations. They perpetually cry tayretcl! oh! the poor little thing! grieving for the sun and moon: for' when these planets are obscured, they always fear that they are entirely extinguished.
